{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu) Chapter 6, verses 41–42 prescribe the conduct for the parivrajaka, or wandering ascetic (also called a renouncer or sannyāsin in this context), who enters the final āśrama after the forest-dweller stage.**[^1]\n\nThese verses state:\n\n> Having gone forth from his house, furnished with the means of purification, a sage should **wander as an ascetic**, indifferent to those desires that have been gratified. // Mn_6.41 //  \n> He should **always wander alone, without a companion**, for the sake of perfection; seeing the perfection of one who is alone, he neither abandons nor is abandoned. // Mn_6.42 //\n\nThe key conduct emphasized here is **wandering without attachment** (to past pleasures) and **solitary wandering** (alone, without companions) to attain spiritual perfection. This fits the parivrajaka's life of renunciation, as described in the broader section on the ascetic stage (starting ~Mn_6.33), which continues with further rules like being without fire/home, begging in villages, equanimity, etc.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 6 (translation), from the opening context of the ascetic rules. `/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/`\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 6, verses 33–85 (full chapter on forest-dweller transitioning to ascetic). `/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/`",
